<li id="cite_note-17"><b><a href="#cite_ref-17" title="">^</a></b> There is some debate, however, regarding the location of the translations of the non-Pentateuch books. See Dines. One theory, that even the Pentateuch reflects variant "local" forms, is criticized in Emmanuel Tov, <i>The Text Critical Use of The Septuagint in Biblical Research,</i> 2nd edn., Jerusalem: Simor, 1997.</li>
<li id="cite_note-18"><b><a href="#cite_ref-18" title="">^</a></b> Greek-speaking Judaism survived, however, on a smaller scale into the medieval period. Cf. Natalio Fernández Marcos, <i>The Septuagint in Context: Introduction to the Greek Bible,</i> Leiden: Brill, 2000.</li>
